### Important Functions
myconvert = function(xl) {
  if(stringr::str_ends(xl, "XLS") | stringr::str_ends(xl, "xls")){
  v=try(readxl::read_xls(paste0(dird, xl)), silent = TRUE)
  }
  else{
    v = NA
  }
  v
}
getmode <- function(v) {
   uniqv <- unique(v)
   uniqv[which.max(tabulate(match(v, uniqv)))]
}

Question 4

MS page 12,13 Read pages 12 and 13 about random sampling designs and answer the following:

  1. What are the names of the four random sampling designs (1 simple and 3 more complex). Simple random sampling, stratified random sampleing, cluster sampling, & systematic sampling.
  2. Give a brief description of each.
    - Simple random sampling is when you simply select experimental units from a population at random in a way where each experimental unit has a chance of being selected equally, an example could be using a number generator.
    - Stratified random sampleing is when the researcher divedes the entire population into differnt subgroups or strata, then randomly selcts the subjects proportionally from the different strata
    - Cluster sampling is when the researcher splits a population into clusters, then randomly select some of the clusters and include all members from those clusters in the sample.
    - Systematic sampling is when the researcher splits a population into groups, then randomly select some members from each group to be in the sample.

  1. Use the results, part d, to construct a Pareto diagram for the data
RL = c("None","Both","LegsO","WheelsO")
l <- rep(x = RL, times = freq)

pareto <- function(x, mn = "Pareto barplot", ...) {  # x is a vector
  x.tab = table(x)
  xx.tab = sort(x.tab, decreasing = TRUE, index.return = FALSE)
  cumsum(as.vector(xx.tab)) -> cs
  length(x.tab) -> lenx
  bp <- barplot(xx.tab, ylim = c(0,max(cs)),las = 2)
  lb <- seq(0,cs[lenx], l = 11)
  axis(side = 4, at = lb, labels = paste(seq(0, 100, length = 11), "%", sep = ""), las = 1, line = -1, col = "Blue", col.axis = "Red")
  for(i in 1:(lenx-1)){
    segments(bp[i], cs[i], bp[i+1], cs[i+1], col = i, lwd = 2)
  }
  title(main = mn, ...)
}

pareto(l)

Question 13

MS 2.80 - pg 72 : Mongolian desert ants. The Journal of Biogeography (Dec. 2003) published an article on the first comprehensive study of ants in Mongolia (Central Asia). Botanists placed seed baits at 11 study sites and observed the ant species attracted to each site. Some of the data recorded at each study site are provided in the table at the top of p. 73.

ants <- myconvert("GOBIANTS.XLS")
ants

  1. Find the mean, median, and mode for the number of ant species discovered at the 11 sites. Interpret each of these values.
# Mean, the average number of ant species at each site if you divide the sum of the ant species by the number of sites.
mean(ants$AntSpecies)
## [1] 12.81818
# Median, the middle value of ant species found in all of the sites (number of ant species in the middle site).
median(ants$AntSpecies)
## [1] 5
# Mode, the most frequently occuring number of ant species in each site.
getmode(ants$AntSpecies)
## [1] 5
  1. Which measure of central tendency would you recommend to describe the center of the number of ant species distribution? Explain. In this case, median. The main reason being that certain sites have a abnormal ammount of ant species, inflating the species amount fo the rest of the sites, this is why mean wouldn't be effective here. Mode is ok in this case, but if the data was a little bit different, I would think that the mode would be completly off like the mean, in comparision to the median.
  2. Find the mean, median, and mode for the total plant cover percentage at the 5 Dry Steppe sites only.
SteppePlant = ants[ants$Region == "Dry Steppe",]$PlantCov
mean(SteppePlant)
## [1] 40.4
median(SteppePlant)
## [1] 40
getmode(SteppePlant)
## [1] 40
  1. Find the mean, median, and mode for the total plant cover percentage at the 6 Gobi Desert sites only.
GobiPlant = ants[ants$Region == "Gobi Desert",]$PlantCov
mean(GobiPlant)
## [1] 28

## [1] 26

Question 14

MS 2.84 - pg 74 : Speed of light from galaxies. Astronomers theorize that cold dark matter (CDM) caused the formation of galaxies. The theoretical CDM model requires an estimate of the velocity of light emitted from the galaxy. The Astronomical Journal (July, 1995) published a study of galaxy velocities. One galaxy, named A1775, is thought to be a double cluster; that is, two clusters of galaxies in close proximity. Fifty-one velocity observations (in kilometers per second, km/s) from cluster A1775 are listed in the table.

galaxy <- myconvert("GALAXY2.xls")
head(galaxy)
## # A tibble: 6 × 1
##   VELOCITY
##      <dbl>
## 1    22922
## 2    20210
## 3    21911
## 4    19225
## 5    18792
## 6    21993
  1. Use a graphical method to describe the velocity distribution of galaxy cluster A1775.
hist(galaxy$VELOCITY)

  1. Examine the graph, part a. Is there evidence to support the double cluster theory? Explain. Yes there is evidence to support the double cluster theory because their are two major points of frequency in comparison to just one.

  2. Calculate numerical descriptive measures (e.g., mean and standard deviation) for galaxy velocities in cluster A1775. Depending on your answer to part b, you may need to calculate two sets of numerical descriptive measures, one for each of the clusters (say, A1775A and A1775B) within the double cluster.

center = (max(galaxy$VELOCITY) - min(galaxy$VELOCITY))/2 + min(galaxy$VELOCITY)
center
## [1] 21704
# A1775A
A1775A = galaxy[galaxy$VELOCITY < center,]
summary(A1775A)
##     VELOCITY    
##  Min.   :18499  
##  1st Qu.:19111  
##  Median :19408  
##  Mean   :19462  
##  3rd Qu.:19740  
##  Max.   :20785
mean(A1775A$VELOCITY)
## [1] 19462.24
sd(A1775A$VELOCITY)
## [1] 532.2868
# A1775B
A1775B = galaxy[galaxy$VELOCITY >= center,]
summary(A1775B)
##     VELOCITY    
##  Min.   :21911  
##  1st Qu.:22541  
##  Median :22780  
##  Mean   :22838  
##  3rd Qu.:23106  
##  Max.   :24909
mean(A1775B$VELOCITY)
## [1] 22838.47
sd(A1775B$VELOCITY)
## [1] 560.9767
  1. Suppose you observe a galaxy velocity of 20,000 km/s. Is this galaxy likely to belong to cluster A1775A or A1775B? Explain. Cluster A1775A because 20,000 km/s is less than the center (21,704 km/s) therefore putting it in the lower end cluster, in this case, A1775A.
